          "id": "security_safeguards",
          "title": "Technical Safeguards",
          "type": "whiteboard",
          "x": 10,
          "y": 2,
          "fact": "HIPAA's Security Rule demands three types of safeguards: Administrative (policies, training, risk assessments), Physical (locks, badge access, workstation security), and Technical (encryption, access controls, audit logs). The Three A's: Authentication (prove who you are), Authorization (prove you should have access), and Audit (prove what you did). Fun detail: encryption is technically 'addressable' under HIPAA — meaning you must implement it OR document why an equivalent alternative protects the data. In practice, nearly every organization encrypts because there's no good alternative. Strong passwords, automatic logoffs, and encryption are the walls that keep the vault secure."
        }
      ],
